[[Category:日本の律令制]]

{{redirect|Ushimaki|For the district in Moriyama Ward, Nagoya, Aichi Prefecture, see {{ill|Ushimaki (Nagoya)|ja|牛牧 (名古屋市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ushimaki (Nagoya)|qq=}}}}  
'''{{ill|Shokoku Maki|ja|諸国牧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shokoku Maki|qq=}}''' (しょこくまき) refers to the pastures developed and managed by the [[:en:Ministry of War (pre-modern Japan)|Ministry of War]] in ancient Japan. These pastures primarily served as breeding grounds for [[:en:Horses in warfare|warhorses]], horses for the aristocracy ({{ill|tribute horses|ja|貢馬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tribute horses|qq=}}), and {{ill|post horses|ja|伝馬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/post horses|qq=}} for relay stations. Additionally, to accommodate horses and cattle gathered from the Shokoku Maki, separate pastures called '''{{ill|Kintō Maki|ja|近都牧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kintō Maki|qq=}}''' were established in Kyushu and around the Kinai region for free-range grazing. This article covers both Shokoku Maki and Kintō Maki.

* Apart from these official pastures, the {{ill|Imperial Stables Bureau|ja|内厩寮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Stables Bureau|qq=}} also managed imperial pastures known as {{ill|Chokushi Maki|ja|勅旨牧|1=Chokushi Maki|2=ja|3=勅旨牧|4=zh|5=勅旨牧|6=fr|7=Chokushi Maki|8=de|9=Chokushi Maki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chokushi Maki|13=User:Immanuelle/Chokushi Maki|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
The exact time when the '''Shokoku Maki''' and '''Kintō Maki''' were established is unclear, but they are believed to have originated in the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]].  
Shokoku Maki were pastures under the jurisdiction of the [[:en:Ministry of War (pre-modern Japan)|Ministry of War]]. According to the [[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]], there were 24 horse pastures in 18 provinces, 12 cattle pastures, and 3 combined horse and cattle pastures, totaling 39 official pastures. Each year, five-year-old horses from these pastures were sent to the {{ill|Left and Right Stables Bureau|ja|左右馬寮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Left and Right Stables Bureau|qq=}}, while those from the pastures in the western provinces ([[:en:Saikaidō|Saikaidō]]) were sent to the [[:en:Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu (Japan)]].  

The '''{{ill|Kintō Maki|ja|近都牧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kintō Maki|qq=}}''' were pastures set up to allow these tribute horses and cattle to graze freely. These were primarily located in [[:en:Kyushu|Kyushu]] and around the {{ill|Kinai|ja|近畿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinai|qq=}} region.

Under the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]], each pasture was managed by:
- One '''{{ill|Makichō|ja|牧長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makichō|qq=}}''' (chief overseer of the pasture),
- One '''{{ill|Makichō (scribe)|ja|牧帳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makichō (scribe)|qq=}}''' (scribe responsible for administrative records),
- Two '''{{ill|Makiko|ja|牧子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makiko|qq=}}''' (caretakers) for every 100 horses or cattle.

The [[:en:Kokushi (official)|Provincial governor]] supervised these officials.  
At the central government level, the {{ill|Hyōbashi|ja|兵馬司|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyōbashi|qq=}} oversaw all pastures, both state-owned and private. Horses deemed suitable for riding were sent to military garrisons, where wealthier [[:en:Soldier|soldiers]] cared for them, while lower-quality horses were used as relay station mounts. This system ensured state control over the supply and management of cavalry horses.  

If pasture officials (Makichō, Makichō scribes, and Makiko caretakers) allowed the horses to become emaciated, lost animals, or failed to meet the mandated increase of 60 foals per 100 breeding mares, they were punished. Conversely, those who exceeded the quota were rewarded with rice.

